<p style="text-align:justify;">extensive meadows &#8211; without any occurrence worthy of notice<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The country was in a manner covered with wild beasts of Every description<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  We crossed three Rivers viz <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Clear Water River</span>, <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Heart River</span> &#8211; and <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Ball River</span><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  It was only on the banks of these Rivers that appeared trees &#8211; which however consisted of only a few scattered dwarfish Poplars<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p class="positiveIndent">The fifth night being within a short distance of the Shayann Camp we made the necessary preparations for entering it in the morning<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Rattle snake</span> and M<sup>r</sup> <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Jessuame</span> charged their <span style="text-decoration:underline;">pipes of Peace</span> placed them on green branches in Solemn Silence &#8211; which lasted for some <span class="DelHand-author">time</span> <span class="AddHand-author">mi</span>nutes when the Chief gave a lamentable song, which the others <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Chorused</span> at the end by a heavy murmur as thanksgiving<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Then a Young man performed the ordinary ceremony and concluded by a long speech in favour of the Chief &#8211; setting forth in the brightest colours all his exploits and good qualities<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  M<sup>r</sup> <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Jessaume</span> who was the owner of the other pipe was called upon to go through his part<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  This he declined he looked awkward and I felt for the poor man<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  A Young Indian perceiving</p>
